h79pPYBWx7Ni6bIG2GYRVi_q7RZKHEFyA ) and much lower fidelity avatars than wh=
at you can get on Roblox and yet when you have the headset on, I have memor=
ies of meetings and I remember the room that I was in and my memory is of t=
he virtual room because that presence was so compelling. Is that the case w=
ith when you=E2=80=99re looking at a 2D plane looking in a window or to rea=
lly make this land, is this a case where being fully immersive is going to =
be important?*

*DB:* Yeah, so one thing is, I think when you speak about this experience, =
it highlights some of the really interesting things around immersive advert=
ising. Those memories, just like you had with your meeting almost start to =
feel real in a way. I think there=E2=80=99s probably a little bit of a grad=
uation from the depth of the memories you might make on a phone to a large =
screen to a full VR headset, but in a fairly large gaming screen, my feelin=
g is those memories are pretty profound and pretty embedded there. I rememb=
er when we had a Roblox holiday party when we first introduced voice on the=
 platform because we were in the midst of COVID and all of this and we were=
 all hanging out. I still have profound memories of that, literally going t=
o the bar in the holiday party and walking by people, I can remember that a=
s if it was real.

*Is that just because it=E2=80=99s a big screen, is it because you are actu=
ally taking action to move around?*

*DB:* Yeah. I have a theory on this and this is, I don=E2=80=99t know if yo=
u=E2=80=99ve ever seen these people that go through a deck of 52 cards and =
memorize all 52 cards and then play the cards back and very quickly they ca=
n memorize the whole deck, some people in two or three minutes. Behind the =
scenes, those people are building a 3D mnemonic representation of that, so =
they=E2=80=99re literally constructing a palace in their mind of a 3D thing=
 and then the 3D memories are so profound that to, recurs back on the cards=
, they just play back the 3D palace they=E2=80=99ve built in their head and=
 that=E2=80=99s how they remember the cards, not by the numbers, not by the=
 pictures of the card, by the 3D memory. So I do think there=E2=80=99s some=
thing inherent in the way we remember certain things that=E2=80=99s very sp=
atial and I think that taps into that feeling you had of remembering that e=
xperience.

*Yeah, I mean this is for sure how my memory works, to do sort of like a se=
lf-examination. It=E2=80=99s the physical tactile environment that is the s=
trongest memories and what calls them back. Does that mean that for all of =
this to really land =E2=80=94 really getting into a proper Metaverse with a=
 headset in a 3D environment, that is when this really takes off like a roc=
ket? Is that going to need to be an inflection point or is it the reality t=
hat it=E2=80=99s just going to keep being the same pattern you=E2=80=99ve b=
een building using your four core growth levers? Or do you think that that =
moment is coming?*

*DB:* I think they=E2=80=99re both going to happen. I think we will see mor=
e and more just the screens we have in our lives, whether it=E2=80=99s the =
living room, a console, a phone, a VR headset, the screen in front of me, t=
hose memories are going to feel real, because we have agency, we can walk a=
round with the person, we can see the body language, all of those things. A=
s VR headsets get better, all the way to the stuff we see in visionary futu=
re movies where they melt away and we=E2=80=99re fully immersed, I think I =
would almost see that as an accelerant, but not a necessary accelerant. I t=
hink the growth we=E2=80=99re showing continues on with the current hardwar=
e and then one could view that as an accelerant.

Roblox=E2=80=99s Future

*How are you thinking these days about platform risk, to the extent this do=
es matter? We=E2=80=99ve talked in the past about Apple, for example. You=
=E2=80=99ve since launched on the Quest ( https://devforum.roblox.com/t/rob=
lox-is-coming-to-meta-quest/2465291 ) that I mentioned earlier, and Roblox =
has taken this approach of =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re going to be on every plat=
form=E2=80=9D. That=E2=80=99s one of your four growth levers and you=E2=80=
=99re now on the PlayStation ( https://blog.playstation.com/2023/09/14/robl=
ox-coming-to-playstation-on-october-10/ ) and 15 million downloads in just =
a couple of weeks. At the end of the day though, if this actually ends up b=
eing the big deal, that is a pretty important dependency on Apple and on Fa=
cebook. Are you still feeling very confident about your long-term position =
with those platforms, relatively speaking?*

*DB:* Yeah, we=E2=80=99ve got some really good partners out there: Google, =
Apple, Microsoft, Meta. They=E2=80=99re all great partners, they all partic=
ipate in our success on their platform just like they would hope to. So I a=
ctually feel we=E2=80=99re pretty aligned with all of our partners.

*Well, that=E2=80=99s good. I know we=E2=80=99re not going to get into too =
many specifics, so I will take that, I=E2=80=99ll accept that as an answer.=
*

*One of the interesting points, other points you mentioned on the call abou=
t this AI is someone asked a question about the relative number of creators=
 on Roblox, it=E2=80=99s a very small percentage of users, to this idea of =
AI making everyone a creator =E2=80=94 do you think it=E2=80=99ll just be n=
atural that people who are building businesses on Roblox, and you mentioned=
 you forecast there=E2=80=99s going to be a billion-dollar business that is=
 going to be articulated in the immediate future =E2=80=94 do you see that =
as being simpatico over time? Or, will there be a long run shift to just Ro=
blox as Roblox and everyone is a creator in some respects means that no one=
 is a creator? That=E2=80=99s not quite the way to put it, but I=E2=80=99m =
curious how you see this shift over time.*

*DB:* I think there=E2=80=99s enormous headroom for experience creation. Ro=
blox Experiences are getting better all the time, they=E2=80=99re getting m=
ore high fidelity, the teams are getting larger. I think that=E2=80=99s goi=
ng to just keep going on and on. I think it will be complemented, rather th=
an maybe compete, with the creation you and I would do naturally. So, I thi=
nk more and more experiences themselves will host in experience creation.

An example I=E2=80=99ve used a lot is I=E2=80=99m a huge fan of Project Run=
way and I used to talk about, someday as we have higher fidelity and higher=
 technology, there=E2=80=99s going to be a Project Runway experience where =
you go in and you cut fabric and you drape it on a mannequin and you have a=
 sewing machine and you compete. We actually have experiences that are gett=
ing close to that.

What I think we=E2=80=99re going to see though is AI supplement those exper=
iences and you=E2=80=99re going to start to see creativity that you can=E2=
=80=99t even do in the physical world. For example, go into the virtual Pro=
ject Runway and create everything with a voice prompt, which is, =E2=80=9CY=
es, I=E2=80=99d like some purple velour fabric. I=E2=80=99d like to cut it =
in the rough shape of an evening gown. I=E2=80=99d like to add some sparkle=
s here.=E2=80=9D So I actually see enhanced creation, and it won=E2=80=99t =
just be Roblox offering that, it will be the experience creators themselves=
 building, for example, a virtual fashion model simulation where they tap i=
nto AI in the cloud to help augment that.

*Is this an angle that is potentially a bullish for your advertising busine=
ss also? Where I think some of the most compelling advertising businesses o=
n the Internet are where they=E2=80=99ve created huge ecosystems and advert=
isers that are native to their platform. So it=E2=80=99s not bringing in a =
Nike or it=E2=80=99s not bringing in a CPG company, it is Facebook with e-c=
ommerce sellers that would only exist, but for Facebook and this, for Roblo=
x=E2=80=94*

*DB:* I=E2=80=99ll use that in my next investor presentation. That=E2=80=99=
s an awesome idea. One could imagine that, go back to fashion, physical fas=
hion may go through a transformation of either personalization or digitally=
-native fashion that moves to the physical world, and you could imagine the=
 complements. It=E2=80=99s interesting to imagine a fashion design house th=
at is intrinsically native to 3D creation, for example. So actually, that=
=E2=80=99s an interesting thing to process.

*Well, from a more maybe cynical perspective, there=E2=80=99s a bit where i=
f everyone is a creator and there=E2=80=99s this astronomical increase in c=
ontent, then advertising is essential to make money.*

